questions.explanation:
&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;4&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;India export&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is in the &lt;strong&gt;past tense&lt;/strong&gt; as indicated by the phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;in the past five years&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To maintain the correct tense, &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;export&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;should be changed to &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;exported&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The structure of the sentence should be consistent with the past tense.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;India&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;exported&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;12.01 million tonnes of rice and four million tonnes of sugar in the past five years&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Present Simple Tense:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure:&lt;/strong&gt; Subject + base verb (s/es for third person singular).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; She writes a letter every day.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Usage: &lt;/strong&gt;Describes habitual actions, general truths, or fixed arrangements.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Past Simple Tense:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Structure: &lt;/strong&gt;Subject + past form of the verb.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example: &lt;/strong&gt;They visited the museum last week.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Usage: &lt;/strong&gt;Describes actions that happened and were completed in the past.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
The following sentence has been divided into parts. One of them may contain an error. Select the part that contains the error from the given options. If you don&amp;#39;t find any error, mark &amp;#39;No error&amp;#39; as your answer.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
She is / as more intelligent as / her brothers are.

questions.explanation:
&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect comparative structure &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;as more intelligent as&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct comparative structure should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;as intelligent as&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; when comparing two entities.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The phrase &amp;quot;as more intelligent as&amp;quot; is grammatically incorrect and should be corrected to &amp;quot;as intelligent as&amp;quot; to ensure clarity and correctness.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part 4&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;She is &lt;strong&gt;as intelligent as &lt;/strong&gt;her brothers are.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here, the erroneous part is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;was.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The subject &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Very few animals&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is plural, so the verb should also be plural.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Was&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is a singular helping verb, so it is incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct verb should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;were.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;The correct answer is Option 3.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;img /&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Very few animals &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;were&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; as faithful as the dog.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 6px;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The segment &amp;quot;has played alongside&amp;quot; contains a grammatical error. The subject &amp;quot;Two of the world&amp;#39;s best forwards&amp;quot; is plural, so the correct verb form should be &amp;quot;have played&amp;quot; instead of &amp;quot;has played.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;Therefore, the corrected sentence should be &amp;quot;Two of the world&amp;#39;s best forwards have played alongside David Beckham.&amp;quot;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;Two of the world&amp;#39;s best forwards have played alongside David Beckham.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 6px;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt; &lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle; font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;/span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1: &amp;quot;Two of the world&amp;#39;s&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This segment is grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2: &amp;quot;David Beckham.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This segment is grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: &amp;quot;best forwards&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This segment is grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect usage of the future tense &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;will arrive&amp;quot; after the conjunction &amp;quot;When.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;In English grammar, when referring to future events after conjunctions like&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;when,&amp;quot; &amp;quot;if,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;as soon as,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; the present simple tense is used.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;When Serena arrives,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; ensuring grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part 4&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;When &lt;strong&gt;Serena arrives,&lt;/strong&gt; she will call you.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1: &amp;quot;When Serena,&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2: &amp;quot;call you,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: &amp;quot;she will&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;Our team is prevailing&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error in the sentence lies in the&lt;strong&gt; tense and structure of the verb &lt;/strong&gt;phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;is prevailing.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; The most appropriate substitution to correct this would be:&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;Our team is prevailing&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;-&amp;gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;Our team prevailed&amp;quot;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence&lt;strong&gt; is discussing an event &lt;/strong&gt;that has already occurred&amp;mdash;securing &lt;strong&gt;a victory in the championship finals. &lt;/strong&gt;Therefore, the use of &lt;strong&gt;the present continuous tense&lt;/strong&gt; (&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;is prevailing&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;) is &lt;strong&gt;incorrect&lt;/strong&gt; in this context because it implies&lt;strong&gt; an ongoing action or a process happening at the moment.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The corrected verb form &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;prevailed&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is in &lt;strong&gt;the simple past tense&lt;/strong&gt;, indicating that the team achieved &lt;strong&gt;victory&lt;/strong&gt; over their opponents in the championship finals at a specific point in the past.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This aligns better with the &lt;strong&gt;context of the sentence,&lt;/strong&gt; conveying that &lt;strong&gt;the victory has already been secured &lt;/strong&gt;rather than an ongoing process of prevailing.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Our team prevailed&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;over formidable opponents, securing a well-deserved victory in the championship finals.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Choose the &lt;strong&gt;correct &lt;/strong&gt;sentences:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(a) Give me them books.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(b) They who go by train must leave now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(c) The story that I read was good.&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct sentences are: (c) only - &amp;quot;The story that I read was good.&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;(a) &amp;quot;Give me them books.&amp;quot; - This sentence is incorrect. The correct form would be &amp;quot;Give me those books.&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;Give me those books.&amp;quot; The use of &amp;quot;them&amp;quot; is incorrect in this context.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;(b) &amp;quot;They who go by train must leave now.&amp;quot; - This sentence is grammatically incorrect. The correct form would be &amp;quot;Those who go by train must leave now.&amp;quot; The pronoun &amp;quot;they&amp;quot; should be replaced with &amp;quot;those&amp;quot; to maintain proper subject-object agreement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;(c) &amp;quot;The story that I read was good.&amp;quot; - This sentence is correct. It uses the correct relative pronoun &amp;quot;that&amp;quot; to introduce the relative clause, and the verb tense and agreement are accurate.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct option is: (c) only - &amp;quot;The story that I read was good.&amp;quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part of the sentence is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;customers find an best outfit.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error is in the article used before &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;best outfit&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It should be &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;the&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; instead of &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;an&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;an&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; before words that begin with vowel sounds.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For example-&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;an apple, an elephant, an hour.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;a&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; before words that begin with consonant sounds.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For example-&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;a cat, a dog, a house.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;The&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is a definite article. It is used to specify a particular noun, making it clear which specific thing or group is being referred to.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;For example-&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;He is the tallest person in the room.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;best&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is in the superlative degree. The superlative degree is used to describe the highest or most extreme level of quality among a group of things.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this context, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;the best&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; indicates a specific category of outfit,&amp;nbsp;the outfit that is the most suitable or appropriate.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 4&lt;/strong&gt;, which contains the error.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;The correct sentence should be:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;I spend a lot of my time at work helping my customers find the best outfit.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 1: (&lt;strong&gt;No error&lt;/strong&gt;) is incorrect as there is an error in the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 2: (&lt;strong&gt;I spend a lot of&lt;/strong&gt;) is not the error as it is a part of the correct sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Option 3: (&lt;strong&gt;my time at work helping my&lt;/strong&gt;) is not the error as it is a part of the correct sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect use of the phrase &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;brought around&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; when referring to suggestions.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;brought up&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;, which means to introduce or mention.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Using &amp;quot;brought up&amp;quot; ensures grammatical correctness and clarity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;All the suggestions brought up by Nina were rejected by her husband.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;2&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;i.e.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;every summer and always stayed&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is in the present tense as indicated by &amp;quot;They travel to Australia every summer.&amp;quot; However, the phrase &amp;quot;and always stayed&amp;quot; is in the past tense, which creates a tense inconsistency.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;To maintain consistency, the verb &amp;quot;stayed&amp;quot; should be changed to &amp;quot;stay&amp;quot; to match the present tense.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Corrected sentence: &amp;quot;They travel to Australia every summer and always stay in small villages on the coast.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;They travel to Australia every summer and always stay in small villages on the coast&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Tense Consistency:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In a single sentence, the verb tenses must align to avoid confusion unless a shift in time is deliberately intended.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example of correct usage: &amp;quot;They traveled to Australia last year and stayed in small villages on the coast.&amp;quot; (Both past tense)&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example of incorrect usage: &amp;quot;They travel to Australia every summer and always stayed in small villages on the coast.&amp;quot; (Inconsistent tenses)&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;it will be the best possible decision&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Part (c) should be &amp;quot;it would be the best possible decision.&amp;quot; as it&amp;#39;s better to maintain the consistent usage of hypothetical linguistic &amp;quot;were&amp;quot; in part (a).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hypothetical situations in English are often described using &amp;#39;were&amp;#39; and &amp;#39;would&amp;#39;, even if the subject is singular. This is a feature of the 2nd conditional grammatical structure.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Since part (a) uses &amp;quot;If you were&amp;quot; to express a hypothetical situation, part (c) should correspondingly use &amp;quot;would&amp;quot; instead of &amp;quot;will&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;By adopting this change, the consistency of the hypothetical narrative is maintained throughout the sentence, which aligns with English grammatical conventions.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;A&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part A&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The use of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(20, 20, 20); background-color: rgb(254, 254, 254);&quot;&gt;possessive adjective&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;her&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part A&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;of the sentence is wrong.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Her&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is a possessive adjective.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;possessive adjective&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;sits before a noun (or a pronoun) to show who or what owns it.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It modifies a noun.
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Marie&amp;nbsp;brushed them away and returned to &lt;strong&gt;her&lt;/strong&gt; prayer.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Hers&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is a possessive pronoun.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Possessive pronouns&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;show that something belongs to someone.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Some&amp;nbsp;possessive pronouns are&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;my, mine, our, ours, its, his, her, hers, their, theirs, your, and yours.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hers&lt;/strong&gt; is a tragic story. &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this sentence, the subject&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;friend&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;belongs to&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;hers&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the&amp;nbsp;possessive adjective&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;her&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;should be replaced by the&amp;nbsp;possessive&amp;nbsp;pronoun&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;hers&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;to make it grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;A&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;A friend of &lt;strong&gt;hers&lt;/strong&gt;, who is a florist, asks if she can advertise on the site.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;em&gt;​&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​​​&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Possessive pronouns&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;include&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;my, mine, our, ours, its, his, her, hers, their, theirs, your and yours.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These are all words that demonstrate ownership.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the book belongs to me, then it is mine.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the book belongs to her, then it is hers.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;What&amp;#39;s&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;mine&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;yours&lt;/span&gt;, my friend.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;explain me&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the segment&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;explain me&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;, the correct preposition &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;to&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is missing after &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;explain&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;. The correct phrase should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;explain to me&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error is related to the use of &lt;strong&gt;prepositions&lt;/strong&gt; in English grammar.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct construction when using the verb &amp;quot;explain&amp;quot; in the context of giving information to someone is &amp;quot;explain something to someone&amp;quot;. Therefore, &amp;quot;explain to me&amp;quot; is the correct form.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Without the preposition &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;to&amp;quot;,&lt;/strong&gt; the sentence implies a direct action on &amp;quot;me&amp;quot;, which is not how the verb &amp;quot;explain&amp;quot; functions in English.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the sentence is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Please &lt;strong&gt;explain to me&lt;/strong&gt; how this plan did not work.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The erroneous sentence is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;He is an lawyer who works for a prestigious law firm&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the third part of the given sentence, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;indefinite article&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;an&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incorrect&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The article &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;an&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; is used before words that begin with a vowel sound.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;lawyer&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt; begins with a consonant sound, so the correct article should be &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;a&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;correct form&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the sentence should use&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;a&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;instead of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;an&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 3&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;He is &lt;strong&gt;a &lt;/strong&gt;lawyer who works for a prestigious law firm&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;may fall low as 43 degrees Fahrenheit&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is grammatically incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;may fall as low as 43 degrees Fahrenheit&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;should be used instead of&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;may fall low as 43 degrees Fahrenheit&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;as + adjective/adverb + as&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; to make &lt;strong&gt;comparisons&lt;/strong&gt; when the things we are comparing are equal in some way.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;The world&amp;#39;s biggest bull is &lt;strong&gt;as big as &lt;/strong&gt;a small elephant.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Most bats hibernate for long periods, during which their core body temperatures &lt;strong&gt;may fall &lt;u&gt;as low as&lt;/u&gt; 43 degrees Fahrenheit.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;had come earlier&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is grammatically incorrect.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;I would have come&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;should be used instead of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;I would had come&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Third Conditional:&lt;/strong&gt; The third conditional, also called the &amp;quot;Past Unreal&amp;quot; conditional is used to describe unreal situations in the past. It is often used to express regret about the past because the hypothetical situation that it describes is now impossible as a consequence of another past action.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The structure of these kinds of sentences is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;If+Subject+had+V3, S+would+have+V3&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;.​&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Example:&lt;/em&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;If I had seen you, I would have stopped my car.&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/08/right%20%281%29.png&quot; style=&quot;width: 25px; height: 25px;&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;If I had seen you, I would had stopped my car.&lt;img alt=&quot;&quot; src=&quot;https://storage.googleapis.com/tb-img/production/20/08/false%20%282%29.png&quot; style=&quot;font-weight: 700; white-space: pre-wrap; width: 25px; height: 25px;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, as per the points mentioned above, we find that the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Option 3.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	​&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;i&gt;If you had told me about the meeting, I would &lt;strong&gt;have come earlier.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;his choicest blessings&amp;quot;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;Usually, in religious or spiritual contexts, when&lt;strong&gt; referring to beneficence from God, &lt;/strong&gt;it&amp;#39;s more appropriate to use&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;blessings&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; rather than &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;wishes&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is because&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;blessings&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to&lt;strong&gt; God&amp;#39;s favor and protection or something beneficial that one receives.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The term &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;his&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; refers to God in this sentence, so you mean &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;the best blessings that God can give&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;May God shower his choicest blessings on you&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; this is a common phrase used to&lt;strong&gt; express a deep wish for someone&amp;#39;s well-being or good fortune.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;Option 4&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect usage of the gerund&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;keeping.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct form should be&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;keep marching&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; to maintain parallel structure with&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;tried not to care.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;He tried not to care and &lt;strong&gt;keep&lt;/strong&gt; marching forward.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1: &amp;quot;He tried not,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4: &amp;quot;to care and,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: &amp;quot;No error&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This would be the correct option if there were no mistakes in the sentence, but there is an error in Option 2.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Here, the erroneous part is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;that angry.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in the part &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;that angry.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence uses the phrase&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;that angry&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;, which is redundant as&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;angry&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;already expresses the intensity of emotion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct way to write the sentence would be: &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;He was so &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;angry&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; that he slammed the book on the table.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;The correct answer is Option 2.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;learn that she was only ten month old&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error in the sentence is the incorrect use of the word &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;month&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; instead of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;months&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot; The most appropriate substitution to correct this would be:&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;After observing the intricate problem-solving skills and advanced motor development of the toddler, it was astonishing to &lt;strong&gt;learn that she was only ten months old.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the sentence, the phrase &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;ten month old&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;is incorrect because it doesn&amp;#39;t correctly represent&lt;strong&gt; the age of the toddler&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When describing an age in months, it&amp;#39;s crucial to use the &lt;strong&gt;plural form &amp;quot;months&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; to signify &lt;strong&gt;multiple months&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this case, the toddler&amp;#39;s &lt;strong&gt;age is ten months&lt;/strong&gt;, which requires &lt;strong&gt;the plural form &amp;quot;months&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;to accurately convey the duration of time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Using the singular &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;month&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; would inaccurately suggest that the&lt;strong&gt; toddler is only one month old&lt;/strong&gt;, whereas the intended meaning is to highlight their age &lt;strong&gt;as ten months&lt;/strong&gt;, indicating a considerably &lt;strong&gt;greater span of time.&lt;strong&gt;​&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/confusion-points-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Confusion Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct form depends on how you are using the phrase in a sentence:&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Ten years old&amp;quot; is used when you are stating someone&amp;#39;s age:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example: &amp;quot;She is ten years old.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Ten-year-old&amp;quot; is used as a compound adjective before a noun:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example: &amp;quot;He has a ten-year-old son.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The erroneous part is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;brass was risen through about 70&amp;deg; Fahr, while&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In option 1, the usage of &amp;#39;risen&amp;#39; is incorrect instead of this we need to use &amp;#39;raised&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;According to grammar, the verb &amp;quot;rise&amp;quot; is an intransitive verb and the verb &amp;quot;raise&amp;quot; is a transitive verb. We know that we cannot form a passive form of an intransitive verb. Hence, &amp;quot;risen&amp;quot; is incorrect we need to use &amp;quot;raised&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb forms&amp;nbsp;of &amp;quot;rise&amp;quot; are- rose-risen-rising.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb forms of &amp;quot;raise&amp;quot; are- raised- raised- raising.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;#39;By this means the mean temperature of the brass was &lt;strong&gt;raised &lt;/strong&gt;through about 70&amp;deg; Fahr, while the amount of metal abraded was only 837 grains.&amp;#39;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;ldquo;I can&amp;#39;t agree with you more&amp;rdquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The error lies in the part &amp;#39;a&amp;#39; of the sentence.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &amp;#39;I can&amp;#39;t agree with you more&amp;#39; is incorrect as we cannot agree more if we already fully agree.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct idiomatic phrase is &amp;#39;I couldn&amp;#39;t agree with you more&amp;#39;, &lt;/strong&gt;meaning it&amp;#39;s impossible to agree more than I already do.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In English, &amp;#39;I couldn&amp;#39;t agree with you more&amp;#39; is used to express total agreement.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;Option 1&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;A&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part (A)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Double negatives&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are avoided in a sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here are the negative adverbs:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Seldom, Nowhere, Never, Nothing, Hardly, Scarcely, Neither, Barely, Rarely&lt;/span&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;I&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;rarely&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;go racing.&lt;br /&gt;
		&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; He&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;nothing&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;knows about movies.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the use of&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;rarely never&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;part (A)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be replaced with&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;never&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;or&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;rarely&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to make it grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;He &lt;strong&gt;rarely &lt;/strong&gt;goes&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;to t&lt;/em&gt;he movies and that is why he doesn&amp;#39;t&amp;nbsp;know Salman Khan.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;​&lt;/em&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;You should use the phrase&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;ldquo;if I was&amp;hellip;&amp;rdquo;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;when referring to something that actually happened.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/span&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;If I was late for curfew when I was a teenager, my parents grounded me.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/hinglish-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hinglish&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;त्रुटि वाक्य के&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part (A)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;में है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;एक वाक्य में दोहरे नकारात्मक से बचा जाता है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;यहाँ&amp;nbsp;negative adverbs&amp;nbsp;हैं:&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Seldom, Nowhere, Never, Nothing, Hardly, Scarcely, Neither, Barely, Rarely&lt;/span&gt;।
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;I&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;rarely&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;go racing.&lt;br /&gt;
		&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; He&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;nothing&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;knows about movies.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;इसलिए,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;भाग A&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;में&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;rarely never&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;के प्रयोग को व्याकरण की दृष्टि से सही बनाने के लिए&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;never&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;या&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;rarely&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;से प्रतिस्थापित किया जाना चाहिए।&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The error in the sentence is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;that makes me went.&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;went&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is in the past tense, but it is used incorrectly here.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this context, the verb should be in the base form, which is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;go&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; because you are expressing an ongoing or habitual action, not a past action.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;that makes me go&amp;quot; instead of &amp;quot;that makes me went.&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The corrected sentence&lt;/strong&gt;: &amp;quot;&lt;em&gt;It&amp;#39;s your carelessness that makes me go crazy all the time.&lt;/em&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;That makes me go&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is grammatically correct because it uses the base form &amp;quot;go&amp;quot; to express an ongoing or habitual action.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Crazy&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is an adjective describing the speaker&amp;#39;s state of mind.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;All the time&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; indicates the frequency of the speaker feeling crazy due to the carelessness of the other person.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 2&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
